[normal]Questions 
[normal]31-107
[normal]Witnesses: 
[normal]Fiona Campbell
[normal],
[normal] 
[normal]London School of Hygiene and Tropical Medicine, Mark Foster, Commissioner, the Independent Commission for Aid Impact and Charles Nelson, Chief Executive, Malaria Consortium
[normal] gave evidence.  
[normal]Q31 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Chair:[bold] Good morning.  Thanks very much for coming in.  First of all, for the record, I wondered if you could just introduce yourselves.
[normal]Mark Foster[bold]: Mark Foster, one of the Commissioners for the Independent Commission for Aid Impact and the lead Commissioner for the review on 
[normal]Burma
[normal].
[normal]Fiona Campbell[bold]: I am Fiona Campbell.  I am a 
[normal]DrPH
[normal] student at the London School of
[normal] Hygiene and Tropical Medicine.  
[normal]I was most recently in 
[normal]Myanmar
[normal] with Merlin, but I am not speaking on their behalf today.
[normal]Charles Nelson[bold]: I am Charles Nelson.  I am Chief Executive of Malaria Consortium and actually previously of Merlin as well, but am working in 
[normal]Myanmar
[normal] currently on containment strategies for resistant parasites.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q32 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Chair:[bold] Thank you all very much for coming in.  You will know that the Committee visited 
[normal]Burma
[normal] last month and had an extremely interesting and informative trip.  In this session, we are looking at DFID’s engagement with the health sector.  I know that ICAI was 
[normal]reasonably
[normal] complimentary about the work that was being done, but it is a major part of DFID’s budget
[normal]—
[normal]nearly half of their budget for the 2012
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]15 period.  Of £63.4
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]million for that period, £45.8
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]million is on community and maternal health, and £17.6
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]million on malaria.  The question that was raised with us is, given spending on health in 
[normal]Burma
[normal] has been chronically low, 
[normal]although
[normal] DFID has been a contributor throughout the period, 
[normal]whether
[normal] that level of commitment 
[normal]is 
[normal]at the right level
[normal].
[normal]  The point that has been made to us is that, if you wanted to be transformational, it may not be big enough
[normal];
[normal] on the other hand, it is rather too big to be just pilot schemes.  What is your take on whether or not it is balanced right and can it be transformational at that level?
[normal]Mark Foster[bold]: First of all, as you will have recognised from your visit, the needs with regard to healthcare in Burma remain incredibly high, and the overall levels of spend by the Government, for example, remain low compared to many of the other countries in the area.  In terms of the need for there to be investment in the broader health sector
[normal],
[normal] that need is very clearly there and all the indicators point to continuing needs in many key areas.  
[normal]What we have found from our review was that, clearly, the money that DFID had been spending had been well spent and well targeted.  Indeed
[normal],
[normal] the programmes and the plans—the 3MDG programme is now the major focus of activity—look also to be well targeted and working on the right kinds of things.  
[normal]Also
[normal], it looks reasonably well set up to have a meaningful and substantive impact, higher than the impact that has been had before, primarily because there is more funding going into that programme, but also because, with the changed nature of the relationship with the Government of Burma, and particularly the Ministry of Health, there is a chance of working and leveraging that work more effectively on the ground.  There is an opportunity for that piece of work to be transformational in the areas where it is focused.  
[normal]It is of course focused on a subset of the townships.  The question mark is: could you do more by moving out to more townships?  From our assessment looking at the picture, it would be better to say, if you could really prove you could have a real impact first of all in those places, you would feel more confident of scaling and having a broader transformational effect once that had been proven.
[normal]Chair:[bold] You would need two or three years.
[normal]Mark Foster[bold]: There is probably some time to be found.  Learning how to work on the ground there and to be effective, alongside an evolving governmental system, would seem to me to be worth thinking through.
[normal]Fiona Campbell[bold]: I would echo what has been said today.  I would say that DFID has been very good in the way it has used its money in terms of a transformational approach, in that it has not just delivered programmes, but it has delivered them in a way that has been building the systems and the structures.  The joint initiative was a very good example, where they used the opportunity in the delta to work within the system.  Okay, sanctions were in place so there were restrictions, but the opportunities that were presented in supporting midwives, in supporting their transport out into villages, showed what was possible if you do invest in a certain way.  They have used the money extremely well to really show how the system can work better, and that is where the transformation happens.  
[normal]As has been said with 3MDG in terms of the way it is trying to approach, yes, it is only in 42 townships but, if it can show that, in those townships, it is possible to deliver services to hard
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]to
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]reach
[normal] areas and to vulnerable populations, then that in itself shows you what is possible if you put money in, and the money will come from other places in the future.  
[normal]Chair:[bold] 
[normal]So y
[normal]ou think this is about the right level of funding.
[normal]Fiona Campbell[bold]: It is a massively underfunded health sector at the moment.  There is room for additional funding to go in, but 
[normal]where 
[normal]the funding 
[normal]is going in it 
[normal]is having a bigger effect than just the programmes it is supporting.
[normal]Charles Nelson[bold]: I would actually agree with the other two here that
[normal], given
[normal] the sort of acti
[normal]vities that have been going on and 
[normal]the restraints under which we have been having to operate inside Myanmar, the money has been remarkably well spent.  It has allowed the communities that need it the most to get healthcare in a way that was sustainable and engaging the communities that were there.  Clearly, if there was opportunity to do more, more could be done, but that does not mean that the existing levels would not be, in their own way, transformational.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q33 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Chair:[bold] Is this likely to have an effect on the Myanmar/Burma Government?  Clearly they do not have huge resources, but they have under
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]spent
[normal] to such an astonishing degree.  Do you think that DFID might effectively persuade them that what is happening justifies their diverting some more funds?  Is there any evidence they would be prepared to do that?  Do any of you have a view on that?
[normal]Fiona Campbell[bold]: I have been there for two years and, certainly in terms of what has been said, there is a commitment to increase spend.  They have made a commitment to universal health coverage, for instance.  Universal health coverage means that everybody should have access to the healthcare they need.  In order to do that, there is going to have to be a massive scale
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]up
[normal] in terms of infrastructure, staff, drugs and equipment getting out there.  That in itself is already acknowledging that there needs to be an investment in the system.  Actually what you are doing is raising the expectations within the population that they can have services.  That in 
[normal]itself
[normal], you would hope, would ultimately put pressure on the Government to increase its allocation.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q34 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Chair:[bold] From what you have said, although it is nearly 50% of DFID’s budget, and you are a specialist in health so you are going to say that, is it justified to spend that proportion of the budget on health?
[normal]Mark Foster[bold]: Clearly one of the things that we found in the report was a sense that health had been a safe place for DFID to work during the time of the EU prohibitions on working there.  Therefore, it is 
[normal]an area
[normal] where we have been able to build up a foundational position, w
[normal]hich allows further spend of this
[normal] scale to be standing on firmer ground.  There are other areas where we are just starting to think about spending money; they become the areas with regard to governance, which is another topic we may come on to talk about later on, where you will be at the very early stage of spend there.  Therefore, thinking about how to put more money through those channels would be something to be questioned until the ground had been set.  The sense that we had here was firm foundations had been 
[normal]laid
[normal]; good relationships had been established with the Ministry of Health
[normal]; t
[normal]he needs had been identified pretty well.  Therefore, scaling up to a degree would make sense to be 
[normal]the
[normal] next big focus in the 
[normal]early 
[normal]stage of the relationship with 
[normal]Burma
[normal].
[normal]Fiona Campbell[bold]: The other point is that, of course, there are a number of sectors that you could put money into in Myanmar at the moment but, if you look in terms of the population, out
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]of
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]pocket payments for health are a major contributor to people’s impoverishment.  The 
[normal]population themselves are already making that an issue for them.  If we are looking for where people would like investment, then health is a really important sector for them.
[normal]Charles Nelson[bold]: Could I add 
[normal]a
[normal] point about the contribution that 
[normal]Myanmar
[normal] can make to the world?  If drug
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]resistant
[normal] parasites do get out of the Southeast Asia region, then that could be an absolute disaster for 
[normal]Africa
[normal].  There is a contribution to be made by 
[normal]Myanmar
[normal] to the global fight against that happening.  Investment in the right type that allows them to have the surveillance necessary to do that, the health programmes in place to respond appropriately to the finding of resistant parasites, would be a huge thing that must not be missed right now, because now is the time.
[normal]Chair:[bold] We will come back to that in a minute.  
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q35 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Mr McCann:[bold] Good morning.  Now that sanctions have been lifted against 
[normal]Burma
[normal], for the first time, we can provide development assistance directly through the Government of Burma.  Does the Government have the capacity to provide sector support in health and what are the risks of corruption?
[normal]Mark Foster[bold]: First of all, 
[normal]our own perspective was that, while things have opened up, still providing money directly through the Government was something to be thought carefully about.  The new programme around the 3MDG programme is still being largely managed through the fund management vehicle of UNOPS.  Our overall sense is there is a stronger opportunity to work more closely with
[normal] the Ministry of Health about the deployment of these funds and, indeed, to use part of these funds to strengthen their ability to manage this.  One thing we were encouraged by, looking at the follow
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]up from DFID to our review, was their comeback with regard to how much of this energy is going to go into building up the financial management strengths and accountability of the Government, which would then allow, in future, more funds to be put more directly through that route.  The key thing here is it
[normal] is
[normal] still early days.  We felt the fiduciary controls DFID had put in place were appropriate, even though some of the people in the chain felt that they were burdensome.  Our feeling was this is still a time to be really tight; it is a time to be focused, but to deploy some of your funds towards building up capacity in the system to allow future different models.  
[normal]Fiona Campbell[bold]: I agree.  I think it is a very important route to go down, but it is a process.  Capacity is needed at all sorts of levels.  At township level, for instance, where they will be receiving funds and allocating them for services within the 
[normal]township, that
[normal] requires people who are able to manage finances at that level.  I know, just before I left, in the townships that are working, there sometimes are no people who have good financial management skills.  That is one of the things that, at September time, basically they had sanctioned new positions at township level, recognising that you need to have that capacity there, but that also requires them to be skilled and to be supported.  That is a process; it takes time.  You need to make sure that those steps are in place before you can put money through, but I think that is definitely the way that it needs to go in country.
[normal]Charles Nelson[bold]: I would be supportive.  You seem to be getting agreement across the table.
[normal]Mr McCann:[bold] Charles, I am going to start with you for the next question, so they can support your view.
[normal]Charles Nelson[bold]: We will see.  There is a unique opportunity, at the moment, as the bureaucracy is opening up.  Clearly there is strong bureaucracy inside 
[normal]Myanmar
[normal] which, with 
[normal]the right training, actually has a platform on which it can be built.  There is a time for that to be developed.  Certainly in dealings with the 
[normal]National Malaria Control 
[normal]board and so on, they are very enthusiastic to find ways to grow and to get better at the task that they have in front of them, and they are being given the liberty to do it now, which they have not had until recently.  The right kind of investment in capacity building through the system is going to be important, but not rushed.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q36 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Mr McCann:[bold] That is helpful, but can I press you on a couple of other points and perhaps start with yourself, Charles?  When we were there, Mrs
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Latham, Mr
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]White and I met with health ministers.  We met with other ministers that day, and we were continually faced with an awful lot of ambition but a huge gap from the reality on the ground.  How big is the skills gap within the health sector, both at administration level and at 
[normal]medical level?  
[normal]Perhaps you could maybe give some practical examples of where that gap 
[normal]exists.
[normal]Charles Nelson[bold]: The gap is significant, in the sense that the ability to actually control activity from end to end that you need for a good health system has not been there.  They have had a very strong plan in place since 1972.  The plan is clear so, within a plan, it is possible to work to build the skills.  Practically
[normal],
[normal] 
[normal]on
[normal] the point that Fiona made about the townships, that is where it becomes weakest, 
[normal]in terms of 
[normal]the connectivity between the townships and the villages that those townships serve, 
[normal]and 
[normal]the facilities connecting with the communities
[normal]. 
[normal] There are big gaps in that process, but the people there are highly capable when given the opportunity to do it.  The training can be done quite fast, but it needs time to be proven.  There are very practical things of getting a supply chain that works end to end 
[normal]and
[normal] is delivering the right things to the right places, and people knowing how to use that clinically in appropriate ways.  It would be the example for me of where we need to close the gap.
[normal]Mr McCann:[bold] Fiona, do you agree with Charles?
[normal]Fiona Campbell[bold]: Yes.  
[normal]From t
[normal]he experience of the delta
[normal],
[normal] working with 
[normal]the townships
[normal] quite closely and the transition to 3MDG, where we were looking at a sustainability strategy
[normal]—
[normal]a strategy for exit ultimately
[normal]—it 
[normal]would also require us to identify what gaps were there in terms of skills.  They are across the board.  Look at all the building blocks of the health system, whether it is human resource management, whether it is supply chain, whether it is financial management, leadership and governance
[normal].
[normal] 
[normal] 
[normal]How do you run good meetings at township level and make sure you have all the stakeholders at the table?  How do you look at the data?  Where is the data coming from?  Is it reliable?  Is it being used?  What is it telling us about the situation within the township?  What is it telling us about where we should be directing?  
[normal]Those are skills that are developed through use but, if you ha
[normal]ve
[normal] not had that opportunity to date or have not had the staff there—a lot of technical staff 
[normal]are
[normal] doing managerial positions in the township—there are skill gaps across the board, at township and at regional level.  At the national level
[normal],
[normal] there is very good capacity in terms of technical capacity, but how is that then put into practice in terms of making decisions, developing plans, developing policies?  There are gaps, yes, and there is a lot of work to be done to fill them.
[normal]Mark Foster[bold]: I would draw an analogy from my recent experiences in 
[normal]Kenya
[normal], where there has obviously been a recent devolution of the health management structure to the counties, which is a bit analogous to what is happening to the townships in 
[normal]Burma
[normal].  The level of ambition you see is immediately naturally there in these new groups that, for the first time, see 
[normal]themselves managing a particular area, but the level of ambition clearly is out of all proportion to the reality on the ground.  
[normal]I think that one of the things that 
[normal]is
[normal] important about the focus of even the work that DFID does fund in 
[normal]Burma
[normal] around health is to keep an eye on getting the basics right first.  That is around the basics of things like the supply chain, the core skills and the delivery of basic services.  You can start to think too much about structuring the whole health system.  There does have to be health system strengthening activity, yes, but it is about pacing it at the right level.  I would say helping the townships to set their bars at the right level, and then funding practical activities on the ground that build that base capacity, would be where I would make sure that our energies were focused.
[normal]Charles Nelson[bold]: Can I just add one other quick thought on focus?  Getting the data to be able to support and evidence the progress that is being made is a clear gap and one we believe needs to be there, both short term from a surveillance point of view, to be able to respond appropriately to disease outbreaks and so on, but the other is just to provide the evidence and data to support the nature of investment going forward.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q37 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Hugh [bold]Bayley[bold]:[bold] You all know 
[normal]Burma
[normal] quite well, it is clear from your answers, but I am missing something here.  It seems you talk about the need to strengthen the system and then you talk a bit about some of the work you have done trying to strengthen township hospitals and township clinics.  I am not at all clear that there is a strategic vision within the Ministry of Health that is guiding all the things you were talking about, Fiona—personnel, management training, data collection on basic health statistics and so on.  To what extent can the donor community, not just DFID, create a good policy base in the sense of leadership within the Ministry of Health?
[normal]Fiona Campbell[bold]: Health system strengthening is a very misunderstood term as well.  This health system strengthening idea has lots of different definitions out there about what we understand by it.  There is some very good work going on right
[normal] now
[normal].  The World Bank has money, through 3MDG, to work with the Ministry and other partners in country to actually come to an understanding of what we mean by health system strengthening in the 
[normal]Myanmar
[normal] context at the moment.  What are the priorities?  Can we get some sort of shared understanding of what we mean by it?  Can we get some shared understanding about what the roadmap would be to strengthen the system?  
[normal]There is also
[normal] a new technical co
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]ordination group under the Myanmar Health 
[normal]Sector Co
[normal]ordination Committee, which is specifically around health system strengthening
[normal].  
[normal]The work that the World Bank under 3MDG 
[normal]are doing 
[normal]with the Ministry on that is strengthening that platform, and that is an opportunity for everybody to come together to really outline what is meant by ‘health system’.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q38 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Hugh [bold]Bayley[bold]:[bold] To do what?  This is the question.  Give me a couple of examples of programmes of work which this World Bank initiative is trying to do.
[normal]Fiona Campbell[bold]: They have not started yet.  This is just to get an understanding.  As you say, the system is huge and it is multi
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]layer
[normal].  It is at national level.  It is at regional level.  It is at township level.  It is down to the community level.  It is huge.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q39 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Hugh [bold]Bayley[bold]:[bold] Do you understand why I am finding it difficult to get a handle on what is going on?
[normal]Fiona Campbell[bold]: In terms of the system?
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q40 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Hugh [bold]Bayley[bold]:[bold] Look at manpower, person power, planning, 
[normal]training
[normal] of doctors of nurses and of health personnel.  Does the Ministry of Health have an assessment of need in terms of personnel?  Does it try to match its training of personnel to those needs?  Is this the sort of thing that the World Bank programme would work with the Department to create a plan for?
[normal]Fiona Campbell[bold]: That is one element of the health system, so the human resources side of it.  Back in 2012, the Ministry of Health did bring in some technical expertise, from 
[normal]Australia
[normal] in fact, to help them think through their human resource plan for the sector.  I know that the 3MDG fund has in their programme looking at the human resource side of things as well.  It is there on the agenda.  It is there
[normal],
[normal] in 
[normal]that
[normal] we need a plan for human resources, but you will also need one for supplies; you will also need
[normal] one
[normal] for—
[normal]Hugh [bold]Bayley[bold]:[bold] A lot of things
[normal]—
[normal]data collection, etc.
[normal]Fiona Campbell[bold]: They are all inter
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]related
[normal].  There are the beginnings of those discussions and of those plans taking place, at the moment.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q41 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Hugh [bold]Bayley[bold]:[bold] I suppose my question is this: you mentioned the World Bank doing some work; you mentioned consultants from 
[normal]Australia
[normal] being brought in for a particular purpose.  Is there not a
[normal] danger that you have many well
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]meaning donors picking apples off the tree, which they think will be good to eat, and you end up—this is a very bad simile—without an overall strategic vision of how the sector develops?
[normal]Fiona Campbell[bold]: That is back to the technical co
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]ordination group around health system strengthening.  That is a platform for all of those actors to come together to have those discussions.
[normal]Mark Foster[bold]: We highlighted from our review our concern that, in fact, as with 
[normal]Burma
[normal] opening up, there would be almost a proliferation of donors suddenly looking at this area, and there would be an un
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]co
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]ordinated
[normal] activity rushing into the country.  One of the things that I have been encouraged by, again referring back to that piece of work that Fiona has just spoken about, which DFID has been focusing on, is trying to get this landscape of the health sector painted, which is a very fundamental piece of work.  It also helps them think much more clearly about the role of the private sector, which is a massive part of this landscape.  Again, we directed them to spend more time in thinking about how to leverage the private sector more clearly.  The other key recommendation of our report was around just getting some data
[normal] and 
[normal]putting in place, to Charles’s earlier comment, the foundational information, once you decide how many doctors to have, where to send them wi
[normal]th what skills for what purpose.
[normal] 
[normal] 
[normal]Those kinds of things are some really foundational areas.  
[normal]Again I would say that DFID has a strong position of influence.  It should influence these very important foundational things.  Also, it should influence around getting the levels of ambition appropriately set, because the politicians will want to push the ambitions all the time.  What DFID needs to play its role in doing is getting the Ministry of Health to make sure it sets the bar at the right level, in terms of what really can be done.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q42 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Hugh [bold]Bayley[bold]:[bold] Have you, with your ICAI hat on, revisited DFID’s health programme since you have done your report to see what has changed as a result of your recommendations?
[normal]Mark Foster[bold]: These are very early days.  Our cycle for going back is actually more like six months to a year.  It is newer than that in terms of our formal cycle.  Obviously the team leader who led the work has looked back and reviewed what has been going on.  First of all, we were overall very pleased they did accept all our recommendations in the first place.  All of our recommendations were accepted.  Particularly actions around the focus on data collection have definitely been reinforced.  Some of the things around risk management of the 3MDG programme, about making sure that the right structure is in place to make sure this large and multi
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]levelled
[normal] programme is appropriately focused, appear to be happening.  The more pragmatic planning on the township
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]based
[normal] activities appears to be taking place, but these are still early days.  The new programme has only really been on the ground for about a year live, so these are early days.
[normal]Hugh [bold]Bayley[bold]:[bold] I have two further questions.  They are unrelated, but perhaps I should pose them both.
[normal]Chair:[bold] Can you be quick, because you have taken quite a lot of time, Hugh?
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q43 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Hugh [bold]Bayley[bold]:[bold] Is there a need within the Department of Health to look for one of the donors to second some key health planners and health economists to work on some of these issues?  Secondly, 
[normal]Aung
[normal] San 
[normal]Suu
[normal] 
[normal]Kyi
[normal] expressed to us her 
[normal]Yangon
[normal] 
[normal]Hospital
[normal] project.  She wants to see a renovation.  
[normal]W
[normal]e will come back to that; leave that.  Let us talk about secondments only.
[normal]Mark Foster[bold]: Are there any comments you have on secondments?
[normal]Charles Nelson[bold]: It is just to say there do appear to be requests coming from 
[normal]Ministries
[normal] to organisations such as ours to provide support and input.  We have made several proposals through donors and to the Ministry to put in expertise to allow these things to develop.  Those are in the early stages.  I would say that, of, we really are in the early stages because, until 18 months ago, we were not actually allowed to talk to the Government about what was going on and all the work was in the communities, right out on the ground, saving lives literally among communities.  I do not think it is that surprising that, now that the route in is there, we are finding the gaps that need to be filled.  It will be a process of finding the next priority and helping them fill, as their willingness to do that goes, within a plan that the donors can keep a good view on.
[normal]Mark Foster[bold]: More generally, I would say our experience in ICAI is the secondment model to key 
[normal]Ministries
[normal] of key technical assistance is a very powerful way of leveraging our input.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q44 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Sir Tony Cunningham:[bold] You have touched on the Three Millennium Development Goal Fund, and obviously it is the largest fund in DFID Burma’s health portfolio, DFID expecting to spend something like £18
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]million between 2012 and 2016.  I wonder how closely the Three Millennium Development Goal fund follows on from 
[normal]the 
[normal]Three Diseases Fund.  What changes have taken place and what lessons have been learned?
[normal]Fiona Campbell[bold]: 3MDG does not build just on the 3DF; it also builds on the experience and learning from the 
[normal]Joint Initiative on Maternal, Newborn and Child Health 
[normal]in the delta.  That 
[normal]is quite important.  It does not cover just HIV, TB and malaria issues, but it also integrates those with the MNCH issues that are a major burden of disease in the country.  
[normal]In addition to that, it has incorporated this health system strengthening component, so that it is working in terms of those specific disease issues and MNCH, but also in the wider system, which will hopefully have benefits for other disease and health conditions that are not covered by the direct programming under component 1 and component 2.  I think it has learned and it has built on it, but not just 3DF; the joint initiative as well has been important.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q45 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Sir Tony Cunningham:[bold] I know ICAI has had some criticisms of the programme, and Save the Children and Christian Aid have also criticised the lack of flexibility.  In your response, could you touch on that as well, please?
[normal]Mark Foster[bold]: Like we see across the world, actually, there obviously is a benefit in creating umbrella
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]type
[normal] programmes sometimes, which allows you to put a number of things together to attempt to, I would say, have a more holistic solution rather than firing in individual 
[normal]vertical
[normal] pieces.  The danger of those, of course, is either lack of focus that comes from those or inflexibility, because you are trying to move this great liner along, rather than more targeted flotillas of activity.  Our concern with the 3MDG fund was it had been a long time in gestation; it was building in lots of different pieces of the jigsaw puzzle.  There had been some issues with the establishment of the fund management vehicles for it as well, and what 
[normal]I
[normal] call the nimbleness of those fund management vehicles.  
[normal]Our concern was that it was well designed, appeared to have the right pieces in it, is buildin
[normal]g on the right past work, but will it be
[normal] flexible enough going forward to recognise that Burma is changing so fast
[normal]?
[normal]  You will have seen from your visit just how much it has changed in a short period of time.  You might put the clock forward 18 months from now; it will be completely different again.  Making sure that this very large programme with the very large funds applied to it stays nimble, manages its risks and targets itself remains our key concern.
[normal]Charles Nelson[bold]: I cannot comment on the particular design of 3MDG, but I do think that, whenever you are building a system away from something that is fundamentally infectious disease control, plus maternity, which are the basics of underdeveloped health systems, you can use approaches that gradually add things on to a system that is functioning.  As you build the system to deal with malaria, TB and AIDS, you are also building the antenatal care setup, because a lot of work is done through antenatal.  If you can build the strength of the antenatal care system, you can build in appropriate skilled coverage for auxiliary midwives and so on, and then midwives associated with it.  
[normal]Having something to build on and building 
[normal]from 
[normal]something that you know works is actually a strong thing, not a sense of weakness, recognising that the needs will change
[normal] over time
[normal], but you are building a platform, whichever mechanism you use to build it.  If malaria is the primary thing, then build it off malaria.  If it is maternal and child health more broadly, then you can build a wider system from it.  I would not be too concerned at the moment that the focus is wrong, but you do get some very large commitments each time you take on a policy to support all HIV sufferers.  You cannot stop once you start.  It is critical that, as you take each of these on, it is clear what impact it has on the system, which is then able to function with the additional burden that it is given.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q46 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Sir Tony Cunningham:[bold] It is impossible to stop once it has started, or you hope it is impossible to stop.
[normal]Charles Nelson[bold]: It depends
[normal] whether
[normal] you contain it with what you can do and you 
[normal]have the skills to do.  
[normal]I just give the example if you go out to a village health worker.  They are usually volunteers.  They have their box and they deal with malaria.  They do the observed treatment for TB.  If they have HIV sufferers in the village, under the joi
[normal]nt approach that was developed, t
[normal]hey are given the 
[normal]antiretrovirals
[normal] to oversee on behalf of the patients that they have, and that works 
[normal]very well.  
[normal]They have an auxiliary midwife who looks after the needs of the community coming through.  That functions.  The more you add to them, the harder it is for them to be volunteers, the harder it is for them to have the tools available to them in the village, and so you have to build a system further up to meet.  The wider you get, you have to recognise that you are putting burdens on to the system that have to be managed.  I think it is doable but, once you put it in, it is very hard to take back out again, as any health system knows.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q47 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Sir Tony Cunningham:[bold] Leading on from that, it is so important that these programmes are sustainable.  I wonder if you could answer the question: how far past 2016 
[normal]will
[normal] EU funding last for 3MDG?  Do you have any insight into that?
[normal]Charles Nelson[bold]: I have not, no, as I sit here.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q48 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Sir Tony Cunningham:[bold] What potentially would happen if the funding was not continued?
[normal]Mark Foster[bold]: I have no particular comment on the EU position, but we have to recognise where we are in the lifecycle of the work in 
[normal]Burma
[normal] compared to other places, where we worry a lot about exit plans and sustainability plans.  We are still in very much a building
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]up
[normal] of the kind of input of capability into the system here, which is going to last for a very long time.  You have to be aware, as has been commented by Charles, that as you put something in you do add to the list of things that have to be kept in place to hold the system up going forward.  I do believe the commitments being made around 3MDG and other programmes are setting up a trajectory that is likely to be requiring support for a long time to come, as the system is created.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q49 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Chair:[bold] The DFID team that we met there was concerned that the EU did not seem to be firmly committed beyond that 2015
