[normal]Q62 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Jeremy [bold]Lefroy[bold]:[bold] Good morning.  I want to ask about drug
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]resistant
[normal] malaria.  Could I first of all ask whether the resistance is purely to 
[normal]artemisinin
[normal] or to ACTs as well?
[normal]Charles Nelson[bold]: In general terms, 
[normal]artemisinin
[normal] is now being supplied in combination and we are seeing some resistance emerging to combinations as well.  It is usually caused by either 
[normal]monotherapies
[normal] being there too long and/or inappropriate treatment regimes of any type of drug, so it is to both, worryingly, as it currently stands.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q63 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Jeremy [bold]Lefroy[bold]:[bold] We have heard about a lot of additional money that is being given, I think some from the Global Fund and from other sources, to try to tackle this problem.  In your view, what needs to be done and is this enough, given that it constitutes a major threat globally and not just in Southeast Asia?
[normal]Charles Nelson[bold]: What there needs to be is a partnership with the Ministry of Health or the 
[normal]National Malaria Control 
[normal]board in 
[normal]Myanmar
[normal].  There needs to be a focus on the at
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]risk
[normal] and migrant populations, which tend to be along the borders where resistance develops most easily or most readily, it seems.  There needs to be constant surveillance put in and data available to be able to assure that, when cases are found, they are contained.  The only way to get rid of a resistant parasite is to get rid of the parasite.  It is still doable; there are still treatments available, but you have to get to the people and the amount of resistance is getting worrying
[normal].  
[normal]There are still options for now, but not for very long.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q64 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Jeremy [bold]Lefroy[bold]:[bold] What are those options?
[normal]Charles Nelson[bold]: The options are other treatment regimes that still work, but you have to get to people quickly enough so that they are there.  The challenge is that some work done on the Bangladesh/Myanmar border showed that 70% of people with malaria were found to be non
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]symptomatic
[normal], but they were carrying the parasite.  Recognising that malaria is a disease of people, not a disease of mosquitoes—people and mosquitoes transmit it—if people are not symptomatic and are travelling freely, and
[normal] they have a resistant parasite;
[normal] that is the issue.  There needs to be surveillance done.  There need to be blood tests done and serology done in surveillance sites to see where these things are happening and then respond to that.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q65 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Jeremy [bold]Lefroy[bold]:[bold] Sorry, are you are saying that 70% of those tested had resistant parasites or just parasites?
[normal]Charles Nelson[bold]: Just parasites.  If a resistant parasite comes through, you are not necessarily going to see it because the person is not symptomatic.  They are not presenting with fever to have something done about it; you may not know that they are carrying any parasite, but it could be a resistant one.  We just do not know.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q66 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Jeremy [bold]Lefroy[bold]:[bold] You said we do not have that long.  How long do you think we have got?
[normal]Charles Nelson[bold]: That is honestly an unknown.
[normal]Jeremy [bold]Lefroy[bold]:[bold] Is it six months, five years, ten years?
[normal]Charles Nelson[bold]: The amount of resistant examples is growing quite rapidly at the moment.  Along the borders in 
[normal]Cambodia
[normal], 
[normal]Thailand
[normal] and 
[normal]Burma
[normal], there are a lot more incidents than we would be keen on.  Of course, overall incidence is still relatively low as compared to 
[normal]Africa
[normal] but, in the next two to three years, we have to try to be sure that nothing is travelling.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q67 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Jeremy [bold]Lefroy[bold]:[bold] How can we do that?
[normal]Charles Nelson[bold]: An investment in surveillance and just literally responding as these examples are found and finding the hot populations that have these, going in and dealing with them, with th
[normal]e treatments that are available—
[normal]those are the tools we have at our disposal at the moment and it can be done.  Whilst we have tools that still work 70% of the time, you can still deal with the parasite.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q68 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Jeremy [bold]Lefroy[bold]:[bold] Ever since I have been very interested in malaria, this problem has been known about, certainly for the last three or four years.  Why has it taken so long for the international community to really get its act together on it?
[normal]Charles Nelson[bold]: That is a good question.  The thing is everybody knows about it, but there is no plan
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]B.  Everybody is running to try to find a plan
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]B because, when there was resistance to 
[normal]chloroquine
[normal] developing, there was a plan
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]B, which was 
[normal]artemisinin
[normal].  There is at the moment no plan
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]C, if you like.  Plan
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]B is running out, but there is no plan
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]C yet.  There has always been hope that the next thing would be found and that it would take a very long time for resistance to develop, but it is now coming.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q69 [bold]&#xa0; 
